33. J Spinal Cord Med. 2021 Mar;44(2):322-330. doi:
10.1080/10790268.2019.1610618.  Epub 2019 May 17.

Global and domain-specific life satisfaction among older adults with long-term 
spinal cord injury.

Jörgensen S(1)(2), Hedgren L(1), Sundelin A(1), Lexell J(1)(2)(3).

Author information:
(1)Department of Health Sciences, Lund University, Lund, Sweden.
(2)Department of Neurology and Rehabilitation Medicine, Skåne University 
Hospital, Lund, Sweden.
(3)Department of Neuroscience, Rehabilitation Medicine, Uppsala University, 
Uppsala, Sweden.

OBJECTIVE: Although life expectancy after spinal cord injury (SCI) has 
increased, knowledge of life satisfaction and associated factors among older 
adults with long-term SCI is still very limited. The objective of this study 
was, therefore, to assess global and domain-specific life satisfaction among 
older adults with long-term SCI and investigate the association with 
sociodemographics, injury characteristics and secondary health conditions.
DESIGN: Cross-sectional cohort study. Data from the Swedish Aging with Spinal 
Cord Injury Study (SASCIS).
SETTING: Community settings in southern Sweden.
PARTICIPANTS: Seventy-eight individuals (32% women, injury levels C1-L3, 
American Spinal Injury Association Impairment Scale (AIS) A-D) mean age 68 
years, mean time since injury 31 years.
INTERVENTIONS: Not applicable.
OUTCOME MEASURES: The Life Satisfaction Questionnaire (LiSat-11).
RESULTS: The participants were at least rather satisfied with most of the 11 
life domains. They rated the lowest satisfaction with sexual life, activities of 
daily living and somatic health. Having a partner and being vocationally active 
was associated with greater satisfaction with life as a whole and with several 
other life domains. Participants with AIS D injuries were less satisfied with 
their somatic health than those with tetraplegia AIS A-C and paraplegia AIS A-C 
injuries. More secondary health conditions were negatively associated with 
satisfaction in five life domains.
CONCLUSION: Life satisfaction can be affected many years after SCI. The social 
context, participation in meaningful activities and minimizing secondary health 
conditions seem to be important for maintaining life satisfaction in older 
adults with a long-term injury.

